<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/FC59975E-26E8-4A62-ABD8-A570DC6ABF06"><gtr:id>FC59975E-26E8-4A62-ABD8-A570DC6ABF06</gtr:id><gtr:name>Keele University</gtr:name><gtr:department>Inst for Humanities</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Keele</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Newcastle</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Staffordshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>ST5 5BG</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>West Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/FC59975E-26E8-4A62-ABD8-A570DC6ABF06"><gtr:id>FC59975E-26E8-4A62-ABD8-A570DC6ABF06</gtr:id><gtr:name>Keele University</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Keele</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Newcastle</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Staffordshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>ST5 5BG</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>West Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/82CF9C4A-6881-4CBC-9619-BF7A009A0482"><gtr:id>82CF9C4A-6881-4CBC-9619-BF7A009A0482</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>David</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>James</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Maxwell</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-000-23-1535"><gtr:id>45784BB0-9776-4CC3-BB01-52FF1388B59A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Missionaries and Africans in the Making of Colonial Knowledge in Belgian Congo</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-000-23-1535</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The project will examine the role of missionaries and African agents in the development of social anthropology and construction of ethnicity through a case study on the Luba-speaking peoples of Belgian Congo.&amp;nbsp; Research will centre on W.F.P Burton, a leading ethnographer from the Congo Evangelistic Mission.&amp;nbsp; It will reconstruct his ethnographic process, examining how the various contexts in which he worked shaped his writing.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research has 5 key aims: &lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>To contribute to theories of ethnic construction by considering the agency of missionaries and African Christians; 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To nuance work on cultural encounter by exploring how the discipline of Social Anthropology was shaped by interactions between Africans and missionary ethnographers; 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To re-locate missionaries within the historiography of African Christianity and shed new light on the changing nature of the 20th Century missionary enterprise; 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To provide a non-hagiographical historical account of Pentecostalism, an important but hitherto neglected strand of African Christianity; 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To innovate methodologically in the writing of African historiography.&amp;nbsp; By combining a range of sources - artefacts, documents and interviews,&amp;nbsp;- different types of knowledge - colonial, African, missionary&amp;nbsp;- the research will explore the mutually constitutive nature of discourses of identity in colonial Africa.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br />&lt;/li>
